      <heading>Thu Jul 25 (Geb the Merchant) :: A Riot!</heading>
      <slot>18</slot>
      <level>203</level>
      <author>0</author>
      <date>0</date>
      <text>*written on a moderately-expensive sheet of paper*

    I was at that Goat festival thing today, you know, the one that that
crazy Goat cult threw? I never heard of them before today, but whatever.
Some savage, black-veiled Aielman started a fight with some poor men who
were just singing a sweet ballad about the great Artur Hawkwing! The Aielman
started to rant angrily about men singing! And he was waving a spear at them
in a threatening manner too! But anyways, one thing led to another and a
full scale riot broke out. To make it worse, some Blackcoat came along,
and he started to go mad from the taint! I swear it by the Light! His voice
seemed to be coming from everywhere at once. He channeled! Light, that
chills me even now as I think about it. Then, the ground erupted where
the poor lads were defending themselves against the savage Aielman, killing
them instantly! Of course, the savage wasn't hurt because they're in league
with the Blackcoats! They're all darkfriends, I tell you! After the ground
erupted, I got away from the scene as fast as my legs would carry me, along
with everyone else. The last I saw the Blackcoat, he was laughing like a
madman! And the Aielman was too! I think I even saw a Trolloc and other
Shadowspawn too! I swear by the Light!

*signed*
Geb the Merchant
</text>
    </message>
    <message>
      <heading>Mon Aug  5 (Sahra)      :: Escape From Amador (part one)</heading>
      <slot>19</slot>
      <level>1</level>
      <author>0</author>
      <date>0</date>
      <text>   Conal McFaddan owned a small inn in Mayene, and it was there that he
married his wife, Sarai; the daughter of a local farmer whom Conal had 
been buying his vegetables from.  After they married, Conal built a small
suite above his inn for himself and Sarai and they lived there quite
happily for the first few years of their marraige.  Sarai eventually found
herself to be with child and this news both excited and frightened Conal 
for he had heard tales that the Tairen army had attacked the First of
Mayene's guards and were on their way into Mayene itself. &quot;Sarai,&quot; he said
one evening, taking her hand in his, &quot;I fear what will happen if the Tairen
army does invade Mayene. I fear what will happen to you and our child.&quot;
Sarai looked at her husband with concerned eyes, &quot;What do you propose
we do then, Conal?&quot; she asked, already knowing the answer.  

  He looked around their home then finally at the floor, he had to look
anywhere but at her.  &quot;I fear we must leave Mayene, wife, and soon. After
the baby is here and you are well enough to travel,&quot; he looked up at her
tear streaked face, &quot;Sarai, please. I know this is hard, but I cannot risk 
losing you or the child.&quot;  Sarai nodded and wiped her face, &quot;I understand
Conal, but where? Where will we go? Our whole lives are here, we cannot
just pack up our entire lives and leave.  Especially not knowing where we
are going.&quot; She burst into full tears and Conal quickly put his arms 
around her. &quot;There now, Sarai. We will be fine, I will think of something,&quot;
he smiled as he slid his hand over her tummy, &quot;we still have a couple weeks
before the baby is here. We will leave afterwards.&quot;  She nodded slowly and
dried her eyes. &quot;If you feel we must, husband. I will follow you anywhere.&quot;

  A week later, Sarai gave birth to a healthy baby girl and they named her
Sahra Elisabeth McFaddan, after Sarai and Conal's deceased mother.  Conal
was very pleased, announcing to everyone that he now claimed the two finest
ladies in all of Mayene and throwing a celebration at his inn.  The 
festivities soon ended, however and the McFaddan's found themselves on a
ship bound for Ebou Dar.  Conal intended to travel to Amador from there.

  Two days into the voyage, disaster struck.  Conal had been standing on
the deck when he heard one of the crewman yell, &quot;Seanchan vessel, dead
ahead!&quot;  The crew seemed to be in a panic and Conal wondered who these
Seanchan were and why the crew seemed to be afraid of them.  He decided
that he should go below with his wife and daughter.

  He had just entered their quarters and let the door close behind him
when the ship lurched and he heard footsteps overhead and then on the
stairs.  Suddenly, the door burst open behind him, sending him sprawling
onto the floor and over where Sahra slept in her crib.  A woman 
entered, leading another woman clad in a grey dress on a silver leash.

&quot;Where?&quot; the first woman asked, she was obviously the leader.
The leashed woman pointed to Sarai.  The leader smiled and patted the 
leashed woman on the head and yelled, &quot;In here!&quot;
A third woman entered then, carrying a leash much like the one the 
other woman wore, and began to approach Sarai.  Conal jumped up and
threw himself in front of his wife demanding to know what was
going on.  
&quot;This woman can channel and therefore must be collared for the safety 
of others as well as her own,&quot; said the leader.
With that, the third woman advanced on them again and Conal reached out 
and grabbed her arms, holding her back.  The leader looked at the 
leashed woman and nodded and Conal suddenly found himself against
the wall, unable to move.  After a struggle, the collar was snapped
around Sarai's neck and as she reached to try and remove it, she 
fell to the floor gagging.

&quot;You see,&quot; said the third woman as she snapped a bracelet around her 
wrist, &quot;you will be in pain if you do not obey. Now up with you, it 
is time to leave.&quot;
On shakey legs, Sarai stood and stumbled for the door.

</text>
    </message>
